      "narr_en": "The Malacca Sultanate, founded around 1400 by Parameswara, played a central role in the spread of Islam in Southeast Asia. Thanks to the Strait of Malacca's strategic position, the city became the most important trading hub between China, India and the Spice Islands. Converting to Islam through Indian traders, the sultanate laid the foundations of Southeast Asian Islam by merging it with the Malay",
